    <h1>Privacy Policy</h1>
    <p class="updated">Last updated: June 26, 2026</p>

    <p class="lede">
      The short version: Ordo keeps your puzzles, streaks, and history on your
      own device. It has no accounts, no ads, and no way to identify you. The
      only thing it sends out is anonymous, aggregate usage data that helps
      improve the game — and even that can never be traced back to you.
    </p>

    <p>
      This policy explains what Ordo (“the app,” “we,” “us”) does and doesn’t do
      with information when you use it. Ordo is made by an independent developer
      and published under the name Ordo Puzzles. It applies to the Ordo iOS app
      and to this website at ordopuzzles.com.
    </p>

    <h2>What stays on your device</h2>
    <p>
      Everything you do in Ordo — the puzzles you’ve solved, your current
      streak, your archive, and your settings — is stored <strong>locally on
      your device</strong>. Ordo has no servers of its own and no account
      system, so this information is never uploaded, synced, or sent anywhere.
      It stays on your phone, under your control.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you delete the app, this data is deleted with it. There’s no copy held
      somewhere else, because there’s nowhere else for it to be.
    </p>

    <h2>Anonymous usage analytics</h2>
    <p>
      To understand how people use Ordo — which features get used, where players
      get stuck, whether an update helped — we use
      <a href="https://telemetrydeck.com/privacy/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">TelemetryDeck</a>,
      a privacy-focused analytics service. TelemetryDeck is built specifically
      so that the data it gathers <strong>cannot be tied to you</strong>: any
      identifier is anonymized (salted and hashed) before it’s sent, it uses no
      cookies, and it never collects personally identifiable information.
    </p>
    <p>The information sent through TelemetryDeck is limited to things like:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>An anonymous identifier unique to your app installation — not linked to you, your name, or your Apple ID, and not shared across other apps.</li>
      <li>Basic device details, such as device type, iOS version, and app version.</li>
      <li>Simple in-app events, such as completing a daily puzzle, opening the archive, or tapping share — used only in aggregate to see how the app is doing.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      We never see who you are, only anonymous totals and trends. For the full
      detail of how TelemetryDeck handles data, see their
      <a href="https://telemetrydeck.com/privacy/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">privacy policy</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Purchases</h2>
    <p>
      Ordo offers a single one-time in-app purchase to unlock the archive.
      Purchases are handled entirely by <strong>Apple</strong> through the App
      Store — Ordo never sees or stores your payment details. The app only
      learns whether the unlock has been purchased, so it can enable the
      features you paid for. Apple’s handling of purchase information is covered
      by the
      <a href="https://www.apple.com/legal/privacy/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Apple Privacy Policy</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Notifications</h2>
    <p>
      Ordo can send you an optional daily reminder. These notifications are
      scheduled <strong>on your device</strong> by iOS — nothing about them
      leaves your phone, and we don’t collect anything related to them. You can
      turn reminders on or off at any time in the app’s settings, or in your
      iOS Settings.
    </p>

    <h2>What Ordo doesn’t do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>No accounts, logins, or passwords.</li>
      <li>No collection of your name, email, contacts, location, or photos.</li>
      <li>No advertising and no advertising or tracking SDKs.</li>
      <li>No selling or sharing of personal data — there isn’t any to sell.</li>
      <li>No tracking you across other apps or websites.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Children</h2>
    <p>
      Ordo is a calm color puzzle suitable for all ages and contains nothing
      inappropriate for children. Because the app collects no personal
      information from anyone, it collects none from children either, including
      children under 13.
    </p>

    <h2>Your rights and choices</h2>
    <p>
      Depending on where you live (for example, in the EEA, the UK, or
      California), you may have rights to access or delete personal data a
      company holds about you. Ordo doesn’t hold personal data that identifies
      you, so in practice there’s little to retrieve — but you’re always welcome
      to reach out with questions. To stop all data collection entirely, you can
      delete the app at any time.
    </p>

    <h2>About this website</h2>
    <p>
      This site (ordopuzzles.com) is a simple static page hosted on GitHub
      Pages and uses Google Fonts to render its typeface. It sets no cookies and
      collects no personal information from visitors. As with any website,
      the hosting and font providers may process standard technical request
      information (such as IP addresses) as described in their own policies.
    </p>

    <h2>Changes to this policy</h2>
    <p>
      If Ordo’s practices change, we’ll update this page and revise the “last
      updated” date above. Meaningful changes will be reflected here before they
      take effect.
    </p>

